with early endosomes","Degradation within lysosomes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe initial step in receptor-mediated endocytosis is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of clathrin-coated pits\u003C/strong\u003E. Clathrin proteins assemble into a lattice-like structure on the cytoplasmic side of the plasma membrane, creating an invagination that will eventually form a vesicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecycling of membrane receptors\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as one of the final steps where receptors are returned to the plasma membrane for reuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcidification of vesicle contents\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after the vesicle has been internalised and requires proton pumps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFusion with early endosomes\u003C/strong\u003E takes place after the vesicle has detached from the plasma membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegradation within lysosomes\u003C/strong\u003E is the final destination for some cargo proteins but occurs well after initial vesicle formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process is particularly important in the proximal tubule of the kidney where proteins that pass through the glomerular filter are reabsorbed through receptor-mediated endocytosis, preventing protein loss in urine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Receptor-mediated endocytosis allows specific molecules to enter cells through clathrin-coated pits.","Clathrin proteins form a lattice-like coat around membrane invaginations during endocytosis.","Adaptor proteins connect cargo receptors to clathrin during vesicle formation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical P